of Tacitus' is doubtful, and that of his Caledonians altogether unknown· ‚ but that non-Celtic, or even non-Aryan elements of population may have existed not only in isolated localities, but intermingled elsewhere with later immigrants, is not only probable in itself‚ but has been most ably argued from the examination of ancient superstitious, customs, or solklore, seeming to date back to other than a Celtic origin ³.

Neither Caesar nor Tacitus mention any other Celts in Britain than the Gauls; but we cannot suppose that those passing by this name were the only or the earliest Celtic immigrants. If, as seems generally thought, the first Celts were the introducers of bronze, and were the tall race of the round barrows ⁴, their arrival in Britain may be dated back ‘to the thirteenth or even fifteenth century 13.c. ⁵, but we have no clear evidence as to their previous home or successive waves of move- ment.
